Although McCrum called more than 40 witnesses before the grand jury, Perry was not among them – a decision likely to add to a fast-growing controversy.

'That's prosecutorial discretion that I had,' he told the Associated Press on Friday.

McCrum's control of the Perry grand jury became another political hot potato when he was named to the post: President Barack Obama had nominated him to serve as a federal prosecutor, but he withdrew his name from consideration after 11 months had passed without the U.S. Senate taking action to confirm him.

Perry's indictment is the first of its kind since 1917, when James 'Pa' Ferguson was indicted on charges stemming from his veto of state funding to the University of Texas in an effort to unseat faculty and staff members he objected to.

Ferguson was eventually impeached, then resigned before being convicted.

